1. rail cars and isotainers must not have bottom valves;

2. all unloading is "over-the-top" via dip tube;

3. all unloading connections are bolted (no quick-coupled hose connections);

4. special unloading and handling instructions and training.



The worst-case accident under the RMP rule is a spill of the entire contents of a tank car into the area around the railcar at "worst case" weather conditions.  Such an accident would spill 10,000 gallons (105,000 pounds) of CS2 into an unlined stormwater ditch.  The resulting evaporating pool would have a surface area of about 4,245 square feet (i.e., 394.4 m2).  In this scenario, the toxic end point occurs 0.78 miles from the center of the release (see below).



